Matthew Cote with his defense attorneys Thomas Connolly, left, and Rick Winling on Tuesday during the first day of his trial in York County Superior Court. (Brianna Soukup/Staff Photographer)

BIDDEFORD — Patrick Machado was on his way to work the morning of June 17, 2021, when he noticed smoke billowing from his neighbor’s home. 

Machado, a former firefighter, told a York County Superior Court jury on Tuesday that he pulled over, called 911 and approached the house. The smoke was thick, but after kicking in an air conditioner at the house on Hardscrabble Road in Limington, he could see a young man inside.

“I was like, ‘Your house is on fire, you’ve got to get out. I’ll meet you around back,’” Machado testified.

He was the first witness to testify in the trial of Matthew Cote, who has been charged with two counts of murder in connection with the shooting deaths of his mother, Cheryl Cote, and her boyfriend, Daniel Perkins. He also is accused of setting his mother’s house on fire and faces an arson charge.

Cote, 26, has pleaded not guilty. He also pleaded not criminally responsible by reason of insanity, which could result in a two-part trial. If jurors find him guilty, they then have to decide if his mental state at the time of the crimes impaired his understanding of wrongdoing.

Machado testified that he didn’t stay on the scene to wait for firefighters, because he was already running late for work. When he was later called back to the scene by investigators, he noticed that a gray, four-door vehicle that he had seen in the driveway that morning was missing.

