Assistant Attorney General Mark Rucci listed for the jury several statements that Cote [made to police](https://www.pressherald.com/2025/02/05/limington-man-accused-of-killing-mother-and-her-partner-asks-judge-to-throw-out-troubling-statements/) after his arrest, including that he felt “bad about everything,” had “snapped” and that he “emptied the whole magazine,” referring to the part of a gun that holds bullets.

“Those were the defendant’s words to the police to describe the last seconds of their lives,” Rucci said.

Defense attorney Thomas Connolly told the jury his client has been diagnosed with both schizophrenia and post-traumatic stress disorder, “two diseases chewing on your brain at the same time.” Connolly said that Cote struggled with his parents’ divorce and the isolation of the COVID-19 pandemic.

“This is going to be a hard case, and you’re going to have to decide hard facts,” he said.

Rucci told the jury that Cote had told relatives before the fire that he was upset with his mother. A family member testified on Tuesday that Cote had described his mother as overbearing, and that he seemed erratic.

Cote’s trial is scheduled to continue this week.

